ce an increasingly hostile political climate.Drawing on interviews with nine-to-twelve-year-olds, Fernández gives us rare insight into how Latinx youth understand their own citizenship and bravely forge opportunities to be seen, to be heard, and to belong. With a compassionate eye, she shows us how they strive to identify, and ultimately redefine, what it means to come of age—and fight for their rights—in a country that does not always recognize them. Fernández follows Latinx youth as they navigate family, school, community, and country ties, richly detailing their hopes and dreams as they begin to advocate for their right to be treated as citizens in full. Growing Up Latinx invites us to witness the inspiring power of young people as they develop and make heard their political voices, broadening our understanding of citizenship.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aChildren of immigrantszUnited StatesxEthnic identity. 0aChildren of immigrantszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aCitizenshipzUnited States. 0aGroup identityzUnited States. 0aHispanic American youthxEthnic identity. 0aHispanic American youthxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Hispanic American Studies.2bisacsh  aCharacter Education.  aCitizenship as a practice.  aCitizenship as a right.  aCitizenship as a status.  aCitizenship.  aLatinx communities.  aLatinx youth.  aRights.  aSociopolitical development.  aUN-CRC.  aagency.  abelonging.  acitizen education.  acitizen embodiment.  acitizenship.  acivil rights movements.  acritical consciousness.  adeportation.  adocumentation.  aeducation.  afamily separation.  ahidden curriculum.  ahuman rights.  aimmigration.  alegality.  amixed-status families.  anurturance rights.  aparticipation.  apolitical engagement.  apoli